docs.abstract: Learn to see through protesters’ eyes with these podcasts.
docs.snippet: Learn to see through protesters’ eyes with these podcasts.
docs.lead_paragraph: As a medium without visual biases, podcasts give you permission to listen in on other people’s lives by dropping you into the room for a deep conversation or taking you along on someone else’s journey. They can bring you perspectives that may have otherwise been inaccessible and allow you experiences other than your own.

docs.abstract: It was black Americans who delivered on Lincoln’s promise of “a new birth of freedom.”
docs.snippet: It was black Americans who delivered on Lincoln’s promise of “a new birth of freedom.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Neither Abraham Lincoln nor the Republican Party freed the slaves. They helped set freedom in motion and eventually codified it into law with the 13th Amendment, but they were not themselves responsible for the end of slavery. They were not the ones who brought about its final destruction.

docs.abstract: What’s online: Robert Garland’s “Return,” Justin Peck in Miami, Wayne McGregor in London and a class from the L.A. Dance Project.
docs.snippet: What’s online: Robert Garland’s “Return,” Justin Peck in Miami, Wayne McGregor in London and a class from the L.A. Dance Project.
docs.lead_paragraph: Dance Theater of Harlem emerged from tragedy and uprisings; the assassination of the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., in 1968, was the catalyst for Arthur Mitchell, the first African-American principal dancer at New York City Ballet, to found (with his teacher, Karel Shook) a ballet school and a company that would offer dancers of color the chance to show that mastering classical dance had nothing to do with race.

headline.main: A Dance Theater of Harlem Classic With a Shot of Rhythm and Blues
headline.print_headline: Rhythm and Blues, And Classical Dance
